<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>NodeMail — DNS Guide for <%= domain.domain %></title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css?v=<%= v %>">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="app">
    <%- include('../partials/sidebar') %>

    <div class="main">
      <div class="toolbar">
        <button class="sidebar-toggle" onclick="toggleSidebar()"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><line x1="4" x2="20" y1="12" y2="12"/><line x1="4" x2="20" y1="6" y2="6"/><line x1="4" x2="20" y1="18" y2="18"/></svg></button>
        <a href="/domains" class="btn btn-sm">&larr; Domains</a>
        <span class="toolbar-title" style="margin-left:12px;">DNS Setup Guide</span>
      </div>

      <div class="settings-page">

        <div class="guide-header">
          <h1>&#128295; DNS Setup for <span class="accent"><%= domain.domain %></span></h1>
          <p>Follow these steps to configure your domain to send and receive email through NodeMail.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── STEP 1: A Record ─── -->
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>A Record — Point mail subdomain to your server</h2>
            <p>Create an <strong>A record</strong> so <code>mail.<%= domain.domain %></code> resolves to your server's IP address.</p>

            <div class="dns-record-box">
              <table class="dns-table">
                <thead>
                  <tr><th>Type</th><th>Name / Host</th><th>Value / Points to</th><th>TTL</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>A</code></td>
                    <td><code>mail</code></td>
                    <td><code><%= serverIP || 'YOUR_SERVER_IP' %></code></td>
                    <td><code>3600</code></td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>

            <div class="guide-note">
              <strong>&#128161; Tip:</strong> Replace <code><%= serverIP || 'YOUR_SERVER_IP' %></code> with your server's actual public IPv4 address.
              <% if (serverIP) { %>
                We detected <code><%= serverIP %></code> as your server IP.
              <% } %>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── STEP 2: MX Record ─── -->
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">2</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>MX Record — Route incoming email to your server</h2>
            <p>Create an <strong>MX record</strong> that tells other mail servers where to deliver email for <code>@<%= domain.domain %></code>.</p>

            <div class="dns-record-box">
              <table class="dns-table">
                <thead>
                  <tr><th>Type</th><th>Name / Host</th><th>Value / Mail Server</th><th>Priority</th><th>TTL</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>MX</code></td>
                    <td><code>@</code> (or blank)</td>
                    <td><code>mail.<%= domain.domain %></code></td>
                    <td><code>10</code></td>
                    <td><code>3600</code></td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>

            <% if (inboundMode === 'webhook') { %>
              <div class="guide-note warning">
                <strong>&#9888; Webhook Mode:</strong> You're using webhook inbound mode. Instead of pointing MX to your server,
                you should point MX to your email provider (Mailgun, SendGrid, etc.) and configure them to forward to
                <code>https://<%= domain.domain %>/webhook/inbound</code>.
              </div>
            <% } else { %>
              <div class="guide-note">
                <strong>&#128161; Important:</strong> Your server must have <strong>port 25</strong> open for incoming SMTP connections.
                NodeMail's built-in SMTP server is listening on port <code><%= inboundPort %></code>.
                Make sure your firewall and hosting provider allow inbound TCP on port 25.
              </div>
            <% } %>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── STEP 3: SPF ─── -->
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">3</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>SPF Record — Authorize outbound sending</h2>
            <p>An SPF record tells receiving servers which servers are allowed to send email on behalf of your domain.</p>

            <div class="dns-record-box">
              <table class="dns-table">
                <thead>
                  <tr><th>Type</th><th>Name / Host</th><th>Value</th><th>TTL</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>TXT</code></td>
                    <td><code>@</code> (or blank)</td>
                    <td>
                      <code>v=spf1
                      <% if (smtpHost.includes('brevo')) { %>
                        include:spf.brevo.com
                      <% } else if (smtpHost.includes('mailgun')) { %>
                        include:mailgun.org
                      <% } else if (smtpHost.includes('sendgrid')) { %>
                        include:sendgrid.net
                      <% } else if (smtpHost.includes('amazonaws')) { %>
                        include:amazonses.com
                      <% } else { %>
                        include:<%= smtpHost %>
                      <% } %>
                      <% if (serverIP) { %>ip4:<%= serverIP %><% } %>
                      ~all</code>
                    </td>
                    <td><code>3600</code></td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>

            <div class="guide-note">
              <strong>&#128161; Tip:</strong> The <code>include:</code> must match your outbound SMTP provider.
              You're using <code><%= smtpHost %></code> for sending.
              If you already have an SPF record, merge the <code>include:</code> into your existing record — don't create a second TXT record for SPF.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── STEP 4: DKIM ─── -->
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">4</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>DKIM Record — Email signature verification</h2>
            <p>DKIM adds a cryptographic signature to your outgoing emails. This is configured through your SMTP provider.</p>

            <div class="guide-note">
              <strong>&#128736; Setup via your SMTP provider:</strong>
              <% if (smtpHost.includes('brevo')) { %>
                <ol>
                  <li>Log in to <a href="https://app.brevo.com" target="_blank">Brevo dashboard</a></li>
                  <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Senders, Domains & Dedicated IPs → Domains</strong></li>
                  <li>Click <strong>Add a domain</strong> and enter <code><%= domain.domain %></code></li>
                  <li>Brevo will give you DKIM DNS records (a CNAME or TXT record) — add them in your DNS</li>
                  <li>Click <strong>Verify</strong> in Brevo once added</li>
                </ol>
              <% } else if (smtpHost.includes('mailgun')) { %>
                <ol>
                  <li>Log in to <a href="https://app.mailgun.com" target="_blank">Mailgun dashboard</a></li>
                  <li>Go to <strong>Sending → Domains → Add New Domain</strong></li>
                  <li>Add <code><%= domain.domain %></code> and follow the DNS setup wizard</li>
                  <li>Add the provided DKIM TXT records to your DNS</li>
                </ol>
              <% } else if (smtpHost.includes('sendgrid')) { %>
                <ol>
                  <li>Log in to <a href="https://app.sendgrid.com" target="_blank">SendGrid dashboard</a></li>
                  <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Sender Authentication → Domain Authentication</strong></li>
                  <li>Follow the wizard for <code><%= domain.domain %></code></li>
                  <li>Add the provided CNAME records to your DNS</li>
                </ol>
              <% } else { %>
                <ol>
                  <li>Log in to your SMTP provider's dashboard (<code><%= smtpHost %></code>)</li>
                  <li>Find the domain authentication or DKIM settings</li>
                  <li>Add <code><%= domain.domain %></code> and follow their instructions</li>
                  <li>They'll provide DNS records (usually TXT or CNAME) to add</li>
                </ol>
              <% } %>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── STEP 5: DMARC ─── -->
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">5</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>DMARC Record — Email policy & reporting</h2>
            <p>DMARC tells receiving servers what to do if SPF/DKIM checks fail. Start with a monitoring-only policy.</p>

            <div class="dns-record-box">
              <table class="dns-table">
                <thead>
                  <tr><th>Type</th><th>Name / Host</th><th>Value</th><th>TTL</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td><code>TXT</code></td>
                    <td><code>_dmarc</code></td>
                    <td><code>v=DMARC1; p=none; rua=mailto:dmarc@<%= domain.domain %></code></td>
                    <td><code>3600</code></td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>

            <div class="guide-note">
              <strong>&#128161; Tip:</strong> Start with <code>p=none</code> (monitor only). Once you've confirmed everything works,
              tighten it to <code>p=quarantine</code> or <code>p=reject</code> for full protection.
              The <code>rua</code> address receives aggregate reports about email authentication results.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── STEP 6: Firewall ─── -->
        <% if (inboundMode === 'smtp') { %>
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number">6</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>Firewall — Open port 25 for inbound SMTP</h2>
            <p>Your server must accept incoming connections on port 25 to receive email.</p>

            <div class="dns-record-box" style="background: var(--bg);">
              <pre style="color: var(--text); font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;">
<span style="color: var(--text-muted);"># UFW (Ubuntu/Debian)</span>
sudo ufw allow 25/tcp

<span style="color: var(--text-muted);"># iptables</span>
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 25 -j ACCEPT

<span style="color: var(--text-muted);"># Check if port 25 is open</span>
sudo ss -tlnp | grep :25</pre>
            </div>

            <div class="guide-note warning">
              <strong>&#9888; Cloud providers:</strong> AWS, GCP, Azure, and Oracle Cloud <strong>block port 25 by default</strong>.
              You may need to request port 25 to be unblocked, or use webhook inbound mode instead.
              Hetzner and most dedicated server providers allow port 25.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <% } %>

        <!-- ─── STEP 7: Verify ─── -->
        <div class="guide-step">
          <div class="step-number"><%= inboundMode === 'smtp' ? '7' : '6' %></div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h2>Verify your configuration</h2>
            <p>After adding all DNS records, wait 5–30 minutes for propagation, then verify.</p>

            <div style="display:flex; gap: 12px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
              <form method="POST" action="/domains/<%= domain._id %>/verify">
                <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">&#128269; Verify DNS Records Now</button>
              </form>
              <a href="https://mxtoolbox.com/SuperTool.aspx?action=mx:<%= domain.domain %>" target="_blank" class="btn">
                &#127760; Check on MXToolbox
              </a>
              <a href="https://www.mail-tester.com" target="_blank" class="btn">
                &#128231; Test with Mail-Tester
              </a>
            </div>

            <div class="guide-note" style="margin-top: 16px;">
              <strong>&#128161; Testing:</strong> After verification passes, send a test email to an external address (Gmail, Outlook)
              and check if it arrives. Also try sending <em>to</em> your domain to confirm inbound works.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── Quick Reference ─── -->
        <div class="settings-card" style="margin-top: 32px;">
          <h2>&#128203; Quick DNS Reference for <%= domain.domain %></h2>
          <table class="dns-table" style="font-size: 13px;">
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Record</th><th>Type</th><th>Name</th><th>Value</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>A Record</td>
                <td><code>A</code></td>
                <td><code>mail</code></td>
                <td><code><%= serverIP || 'YOUR_SERVER_IP' %></code></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>MX Record</td>
                <td><code>MX</code></td>
                <td><code>@</code></td>
                <td><code>mail.<%= domain.domain %></code> (priority 10)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>SPF</td>
                <td><code>TXT</code></td>
                <td><code>@</code></td>
                <td><code>v=spf1
                  <% if (smtpHost.includes('brevo')) { %>include:spf.brevo.com<% } else if (smtpHost.includes('mailgun')) { %>include:mailgun.org<% } else if (smtpHost.includes('sendgrid')) { %>include:sendgrid.net<% } else { %>include:<%= smtpHost %><% } %>
                  <% if (serverIP) { %>ip4:<%= serverIP %><% } %> ~all</code>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>DMARC</td>
                <td><code>TXT</code></td>
                <td><code>_dmarc</code></td>
                <td><code>v=DMARC1; p=none; rua=mailto:dmarc@<%= domain.domain %></code></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script src="/js/app.js?v=<%= v %>"></script>
</body>
</html>
